## Part 3: Dependency Injection (1 hour)

### 3.1 Why Dependency Injection?

DI allows components to depend on **interfaces** instead of **concrete implementations**:

```go
// BAD: Hard-coded dependency on concrete type
type UserService struct {
    // directly uses PostgreSQL
    db *postgres.Connection
}

// GOOD: Depends on interface
type UserService struct {
    repo Repository  // Could be PostgreSQL, MySQL, mock, etc.
}

// In tests
type MockRepository struct{}
func (m *MockRepository) GetByID(ctx context.Context, id string) (*User, error) {
    return &User{ID: "mock_user"}, nil
}

service := NewUserService(mockRepo)  // Easy to test!
```

### 3.2 Constructor Injection Pattern

```go
// Dependencies passed via constructor

type UserService struct {
    repo   Repository
    logger logger.Logger
    config *Config
}

// NewUserService creates service with dependencies
func NewUserService(
    repo Repository,
    logger logger.Logger,
    config *Config,
) *UserService {
    return &UserService{
        repo:   repo,
        logger: logger,
        config: config,
    }
}

// In initialization
userService := NewUserService(
    userRepo,
    logInstance,
    cfg,
)
```

